t. There is no one medicine or dosage that is correct=\r\n\nfor everyone at all times. Words of power also emerge from certain bhavas.=\r\n\nIn Swami Vivekananda&#39;s writings, some are very action-oriented when he was=\r\n\nin the bhava of karma yogaand some are in the mode of deep renunciation wh=\r\nen\nhe was in the bhava of complete renunciation. It is fruitless to look fo=\r\nr\nlogical principles to tie everything together into a simple explanation o=\r\nr\nprinciple or personality trait. As Mahatma Gandhi said once (to paraphras=\r\ne),\nmy duty is towards truth, not towards consistency. Swami Sivananda wrot=\r\ne\nthese words out of a tremendously deep bhava and samadhi--there is intens=\r\ne\nvairagya that emanates from these words--and there certainly is a place f=\r\nor\nsuch exhortations in the spiritual life. They are intended for certain\np=\r\nersons at certain stages of their spiritual journey and are valid for them.=\r\n\nSuch writings are not to be read intellectually and/or understood\nintellec=\r\ntually--they are to be drunk as nectar from the mouths of men and\nwomen who=\r\n realized the divine and through the tapas shakti of their writing,\nthey he=\r\nlp guide us and propel us forward on our own spiritual path. If we\ntake the=\r\nir words and become argumentative, the fault lies with us that we\nhave not =\r\nread them in the proper spirit or attitude.\n\nWarm regards,\nAditi\n\nOn Mon, J=\r\nun 20, 2011 at 3:48 PM, Narasimha PVR Rao &lt;pvr@...&gt; wrote:\n\n&gt; **\n&gt;\n=\r\n&gt;\n&gt; Namaste,\n&gt;\n&gt; I do not want to drag this on, but these are crucial point=\r\ns.\n&gt;\n&gt; &gt; If one professes to have knowledge he cannot do actions, for\n&gt; &gt; a=\r\nctions are worldly. The atman is entirely opposed to action\n&gt;\n&gt; First of al=\r\nl, note one fact. Long after becoming a sannyasin, Swami\n&gt; Sivananda travel=\r\nled the world, wrote books, gave lectures and founded Divine\n&gt; Life Society=\r\n, among other &quot;actions&quot;! :-)\n&gt;\n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;\n&gt; If he established =\r\nDLS with the expectation that it becomes a success or\n&gt; 10,000 people join =\r\nit or some such thing, then it would become an ignorant\n&gt; action, i.e. acti=\r\non with attachment. If he did the action completely ready\n&gt; for any outcome=\r\n and without a sense of ownership, and as an instrument of\n&gt; the divine wil=\r\nl, then it is neither &quot;worldly&quot; nor binding nor ignorant. The\n&gt; problem is =\r\nnot &quot;actions&quot;, but actions with attachment and a sense of\n&gt; ownership, i.e.=\r\n actions driven by the will and agenda of a limited ego.\n&gt;\n&gt; Actions should=\r\n not be spoken ill of like this. Detached action is a *sacred\n&gt; duty* of ev=\r\nery being. Gods and rishis came back again and again to earth to\n&gt; engage i=\r\nn detached action.\n&gt;\n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;\n&gt; If &quot;the atman is entirely op=\r\nposed to action&quot;, then why is atman (Self) even\n&gt; allowing action? Why does=\r\nn&#39;t it simply halt everything? Or, is all the\n&gt; action happening outside of=\r\n atman? Is there anything outside of atman at\n&gt; all?\n&gt;\n&gt; Some buddhist phil=\r\nosophies coined the term anatman (non-Self) to describe\n&gt; transient things.=\r\n But, in Vedic philosophy, there is no anatman. All that is\n&gt; is atman (Sel=\r\nf). Ocean is permanent and still, but ripples that arise in it\n&gt; are transi=\r\nent and moving. But ripples are part of ocean only and you do not\n&gt; start l=\r\nabeling ripples as &quot;non-ocean&quot;.\n&gt;\n&gt; Atman or Purusha or Shiva is the potent=\r\nial energy of this cosmos, while\n&gt; Maya or Prakriti or Shakti is the kineti=\r\nc energy of this cosmos. Shiva and\n&gt; Shakti are seen as different entities =\r\nby some people, but rishis have\n&gt; declared their oneness. Potential energy =\r\nbecomes kinetic energy and vice\n&gt; versa.\n&gt;\n&gt; Atman is the still ocean and M=\r\naya is the force (kinetic) that gives rise to\n&gt; moving ripples on the surfa=\r\nce. A ripple that exerts itself to move in a\n&gt; particular way keeps collidi=\r\nng with the force and keeps moving hither and\n&gt; tither in a chaotic way for=\r\n a very long time. A ripple that does not exert\n&gt; itself and moves smoothly=\r\n as dictated by the force will eventually grind to\n&gt; a halt and cease to ex=\r\nist as a ripple on the surface. It then becomes part\n&gt; of the still ocean. =\r\nIf a ripple exerts itself to become still, it may even\n&gt; take longer to bec=\r\nome still. What prolongs a ripple is not movement but\n&gt; resisting the direc=\r\ntion given by the force and exerting to move in a\n&gt; particular way (or even=\r\n exerting to become still). A ripple that surrenders\n&gt; to the force will ri=\r\nde the course and die down faster.\n&gt;\n&gt; Contemplate the imagery I presented =\r\nabove regarding Atman and Maya,\n&gt; ignorant/egoistic action and detached act=\r\nion! It is very apt.\n&gt;\n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;\n&gt; In not-so-distant past, sa=\r\nnnyasins remained in ashrams and isolated\n&gt; themselves from society and did=\r\n their sadhana. Swami Vivekananda started a\n&gt; new trend.\n&gt;\n&gt; A sannyasin re=\r\nnounces expectation of things from people stuck in transient\n&gt; material wor=\r\nld and does not depend on anyone. But he may still *give* basic\n&gt; material =\r\nthings to those hapless people stuck in transient material world!\n&gt; For exa=\r\nmple, Swami Vivekananda and his brother monks went to places struck\n&gt; by pl=\r\nague, floods, droughts, cyclones etc and served people. They provided\n&gt; foo=\r\nd, medicines etc (instead of lecturing that body is a transient illusion\n&gt; =\r\nand one should stop worrying about its welfare!) and also did construction\n=\r\n&gt; work. They ignored the welfare of their own bodies, put themselves at ris=\r\nk\n&gt; and overcame maya personally. But they served those still stuck in maya=\r\n\n&gt; without looking down upon them or their needs or maya that trapped them!=\r\n\n&gt; Those who wanted food got food, those who wanted medicines got medicines=\r\n and\n&gt; those who wanted books got books. Renunciation means you do not expe=\r\nct\n&gt; anything from anyone and accept whatever comes to you naturally. It do=\r\nes not\n&gt; necessarily mean rejecting or ignoring others. Overcoming maya doe=\r\ns not\n&gt; require belittling maya or belittling those still stuck in maya.\n&gt;\n=\r\n&gt; The trend started by Swami Vivekananda was continued by Swami Sivananda.\n=\r\n&gt; For that reason, it is a bit weird to see him talking so ill of action! H=\r\ne\n&gt; was obviously trying to inspire a specific group of people for a specif=\r\nic\n&gt; body of work. These words are neither universal nor do they reflect hi=\r\ns\n&gt; tremendous wisdom I have seen elsewhere!\n&gt;\n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;\n&gt; Al=\r\nl this intellectual discussion may be satisfying to some, but the quote\n&gt; f=\r\nrom Swami Brahmanananda in the other mail is very apt: &quot;You have been only\n=\r\n&gt; hearing of all these spiritual things. Now realise them. You have done\n&gt; =\r\nenough study and reasoning. Now do some spiritual practice. First take up\n&gt;=\r\n that aspect of God which appeals to you most. Follow your own path of\n&gt; Sa=\r\ndhana. When you realise God through it, you will feel the joy of realising\n=\r\n&gt; Him also in other aspects and through other paths.&quot;\n&gt;\n&gt; According to Rama=\r\nkrishna, Swami Brahmananda was a gopala who accompanied\n&gt; Lord Krishna in a=\r\n previous life. His words are simple, pragmatic and\n&gt; powerful.\n&gt;\n&gt; I want =\r\nthis forum to facilitate exchange of Vedic knowledge (and I will\n&gt; also be =\r\ncontributing, though in spurts). But I want more that this forum\n&gt; should i=\r\nnspire people to do sadhana and find God. In the end, that 